", "pr_description": "Configurable Generic Constraints for Swift
Resolves #86.

Default type constraints can now be specified for Swift within the config, using `default_generic_constraints = [...]` under `[swift]`. Constraint strings within the list can include multiple constraints, such as `Sendable & Identifiable`.", "problem_statement": "Support specifying swift Generic Type Constraints
Consider the following struct:

```
#[typeshare]
#[derive(Serialize, Debug)]
#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]
pub struct AccountPayload<A> {
    pub id: String,
    pub payload: A
}
```

It is generated as: (we have Sendable in the typeshare.toml file)
```
public struct AccountPayload<A: Codable>: Codable, Sendable {
	public let id: String
	public let payload: A
…
	}
}
```

However, generic type `A` (and others) may also have another type constraint (in this case `Sendable` supplied) so that it needs to be generated as:
```
public struct CoreAccountMenuEntry<A: Codable & Sendable>: Codable, Sendable {
…
```

### Suggestion:

An additional decorator parameter in the toml:
`default_generic_decorators = ["Sendable"]`

And/or in the rust definitions itself:
`[typeshare(swift="Whatever", swift_generic="A:Sendable & AnotherProtocol,B:Sendable & SomeOtherProtocol")]` where A and B are generics specified in the struct. (I added B here in case there is more than one generic)
